49b.title: Cayley's Theorem on symmetric groups
49b.clickbait: The "fundamental theorem of symmetry", forging the connection between symmetry and group theory.
49b.text:
Cayley's Theorem states that every group $G$ appears as a certain subgroup of the [-497] $\mathrm{Sym}(G)$ on the [-3gz] of $G$.

# Formal statement

Let $G$ be a group.
Then $G$ is [group_isomorphism isomorphic] to a subgroup of $\mathrm{Sym}(G)$.

# Proof

Consider the left regular [3t9 action] of $G$ on $G$: that is, the function $G \times G \to G$ given by $(g, h) \mapsto gh$.
This [49c induces a homomorphism] $\Phi: G \to \mathrm{Sym}(G)$ given by [-currying]: $g \mapsto (h \mapsto gh)$.

Now the following are equivalent:

- $g \in \mathrm{ker}(\Phi)$ the [kernel_of_group_homomorphism kernel] of $\Phi$
- $(h \mapsto gh)$ is the identity map
- $gh = h$ for all $h$
- $g$ is the identity of $G$

Therefore the kernel of the homomorphism is trivial, so it is injective.
It is therefore bijective onto its [3lh image], and hence an isomorphism onto its image.

Since the image of a group under a homomorphism is a subgroup of the codomain of the homomorphism [todo: this is detailed on the group_homomorphism page, but we should link it], we have shown that $G$ is isomorphic to a subgroup of $\mathrm{Sym}(G)$.
